{
  "text": "In view of the ability of DP cells to induce hair follicles in non-hair-bearing skin , there is considerable interest in therapeutic applications of DP cells to treat alopecia. A number of techniques for culturing DP cells have been reported, but hair-inductive ability tends to be lost during passaging. Various approaches to preventing loss of inductive potential have been described, including cultivation in the presence of bone morphogenic proteins (BMPs) and Wnts [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . One notable characteristic of cultured DP cells is their tendency to aggregate Oliver, 1981, 1984; , and this has led to strategies for culturing DP cells as three-dimensional (3D) spheres, rather than adherent on tissue culture plastic [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Although there is some preservation of DP marker expression, a disadvantage of 3D cultures is the limited scope for expanding cell numbers (Young et al., 2008) .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "29319761",
